NAME
       find - walk a directory tree and evaluate an expression

SYNOPSIS
       find [PATH ...] [EXPRESSION]

DESCRIPTION
       Recursively descends each PATH and, for every file encountered,
       evaluates the expression. With no expression, the default action
       is -print. With no PATH, the current directory is used.

TESTS
       -name PAT      basename matches shell glob PAT (* and ?)
       -iname PAT     like -name, but case insensitive
       -path PAT      full path matches glob PAT
       -ipath PAT     like -path, case insensitive
       -type C        file type: f file, d dir, l link, c chr, b blk,
                      p fifo
       -empty         empty file or empty directory
       -size [+-]N[ckMG]
                      file size; default unit is 512-byte blocks ('b').
                      'c' = bytes, 'k' = KiB, 'M' = MiB, 'G' = GiB.
                      Prefix '+' means "more than N", '-' means
                      "less than N", no prefix means "exactly N".
       -mindepth N    only act on entries at depth >= N
       -maxdepth N    do not descend below depth N

OPERATORS
       ! TEST, -not TEST       negate TEST
       TEST -and TEST          implicit conjunction
       TEST -or  TEST          logical OR
       -true, -false           constants

ACTIONS
       -print          write path + newline (default if no action set)
       -print0         write path + NUL byte (pairs with xargs -0)
       -depth          process directory contents before the directory
                       itself
       -exec CMD ... ;
                       run CMD for each match; the literal {} in any
                       argument is replaced by the current path. The
                       expression must be terminated by ';' (quote it as
                       \\; in shell-style invocations).

EXAMPLES
       find /bin -type f -name 'l*'
       find . -iname '*.c' -size +1k
       find /tmp -depth -mindepth 1 -exec rm {} ;
       find / -path '*/usr/*' -type d -maxdepth 4

SEE ALSO
       grep(1), ls(1)
